<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-evaluation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Evaluation</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        In the previous chapter, you learned how to capture expressions. The
        complement of capturing is evaluating. Here, you'll learn about
        <c>eval()</c>, which evaluates an expression in an environment.
      </p>

      <p>
        This gives you tremendous power to manipulate R code, but it also
        comes with a responsibility: it's easy to misuse, and it's easy to
        create code that doesn't work in all cases. This chapter will give you
        the foundations you need to use it safely.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <section xml:id="sec-eval-basics">
      <title>Evaluation basics</title>

      <p>
        Here we'll explore the basics of evaluation. The first important idea
        is that <c>eval()</c> takes two arguments. The first is the expression
        to evaluate, and the second is the environment in which to evaluate it.
      </p>
    </section>

  </chapter>
